erican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Ithel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name derived from the Greek, signifying 'blooming luxuriantly, flourishing, rich.'. It is from Ithel that we have first the name Ap-Ithel, then by corruption, Bithell and Bethell."],"variants":[{"name":"Bithell","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Bethel  ."]},{"name":"Bethell","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Bethel  ."]}]},{"name":"Fychan","type":"LAST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Growny","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gramhna</b>, thought to be a corrupt form of <b>Mac Carrghamhna</b> ‘son of <i>Corrghamhain</i>’ (see   McCarron  )."],"variants":[{"name":"McCarron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Fidelma, Liam, Sean Patrick, Siobhan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Carrghamhna</b> ‘son of <i>Corrghamhain</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>corr</i> ‘sharp’ + <i>gamhain</i> ‘calf’ (young bull).","Irish and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Ciaráin</b> ‘son of <i>Ciarán</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘little dark one’ based on <i>ciar</i> ‘black’. See   Kieran  ."]}]},{"name":"Hen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Jennifer  , occasionally used independently."],"variants":[{"name":"Jennifer","meanings":["Of Celtic (Arthurian) origin, a Cornish form of the name of King Arthur's unfaithful   Guinevere .  At the beginning of the 20th century, the name was merely a Cornish curiosity, but since then it has become enormously popular all over the English-speaking world, partly due to the influence of the film star  Jennifer Jones  (  1919–2009 , born as  Phyllis Isley ). Another factor in its rise was probably  Bernard Shaw's  use of it for the character of Jennifer Dubedat in The Doctor's Dilemma (  1905 ).  See also  Gaynor .  More recent well-known bearers include the American tennis player  Jennifer Capriati  (  b. 1976 ) and the British comedienne  Jennifer Saunders  (  b. 1958 )."]}]},{"name":"Sais","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Fernando, Orlando, Angelita, Arturo, Delfina, Desiderio, Dionicio, Edgardo, Elva, Fidel, Isidoro, Jere.","Catalan: topographic name from <i>saix</i> ‘rock’ (from Latin <i>saxum</i>), or an ethnic name for a Saxon, derived from the root of <i>saxó</i> ‘Saxon’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hen Cynwrig Sais ap Ithel Fychan ap Growny was born in 1180, his father, Ithel Fychan ap Ithel Llwd, was -45 and his mother, Adelicia or Eva verch Richard, was 83. He had at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"1180–":"1180–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1230–1314":"1230–1314","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1262–Female":"1262–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1225–1300":"1225–1300","1098–1245":"1098–1245","1314":"1314","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1098":"1098","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1180":"1180","Trefdraeth, Anglesey, Wales":"Trefdraeth, Anglesey, Wales"},"fi":{"1180–":"1180–Kuollut","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1230–1314":"1230–1314","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1262–Female":"1262–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1225–1300":"1225–1300","1098–1245":"1098–1245","1314":"1314","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1098":"1098","1262":"1262